# The nextInt() and nextLine() Problem

Example

```java
Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

int age = sc.nextInt();

String name = sc.nextLine();

System.out.println(age);
System.out.println(name);
```

Input

```
22
Krishna
```

Output

```
22
```

The name is skipped.

---

# Why Does This Happen?

When the user enters:

```
22↵
```

The input buffer contains:

```
22\n
```

`nextInt()` reads only:

```
22
```

The newline character (`\n`) remains in the input buffer.

When `nextLine()` executes, it immediately reads the leftover newline and returns an empty string.

---

# Input Buffer

The input buffer is a temporary memory area where keyboard input is stored before the program reads it.

Example

```
Keyboard

↓

Input Buffer

↓

Scanner

↓

Java Program
```

---

# Solution

Consume the leftover newline before calling `nextLine()`.

```java
int age = sc.nextInt();

sc.nextLine();

String name = sc.nextLine();
```

Now the program works correctly.

